      <pubDate>Sun, 17 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/jwt-with-dancer2/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h4 id=&#34;disclaimer-image-is-generated-using-chatgpt&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DISCLAIMER:&lt;/strong&gt; Image is generated using &lt;code&gt;ChatGPT&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/h4&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I remember the good old days of web application when we used sessions to remember user because the underlying protocol of the web is completely stateless. This was the fallback mechanism when cookie support is disabled or unavailable on the client&amp;rsquo;s browser.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In general, session can be either:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ol&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Stateful: The server remembers something about the client between requests.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Stateless: The server forgets everything after each request.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ol&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;JSON Web Token (JWT)&lt;/code&gt; is something I never used before. I am building web application for my twins, student of year 4. They enjoy mathematics, my favourite subject. I try to keep them engage with fun maths questions. Their school promotes &lt;a href=&#34;https://ttrockstars.com&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Times Tables Rock Stars (TTRS)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; web application where they practice times tables. I noticed they are good in times tables but not something like &lt;code&gt;-2 + 1&lt;/code&gt;. They have been taught, &lt;code&gt;1 + 2&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;3 - 1&lt;/code&gt; but not &lt;code&gt;-1 + 3&lt;/code&gt;. My web application would take care of this gap and many more in their knowledge.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>OAuth2 with Dancer2</title>
      <link>https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/oauth2-with-dancer2/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 17 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/oauth2-with-dancer2/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h4 id=&#34;disclaimer-image-is-generated-using-google-gemini&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DISCLAIMER:&lt;/strong&gt; Image is generated using &lt;code&gt;Google Gemini&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/h4&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Last night, I published a blog post about &lt;a href=&#34;https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/jwt-with-dancer2&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;JWT with Dancer2&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. It was something that I never had chance to play with. I thoroughly enjoyed the journey.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Today, I am going to talk about &lt;code&gt;OAuth2&lt;/code&gt;. This is also new to me. I have read about it many years ago but never had time to actually try it. Now that I am done with &lt;code&gt;JWT&lt;/code&gt;, it is natural that I take a look at &lt;code&gt;OAuth2&lt;/code&gt; now.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
